bug.short_desc: auxprop-hashed with slapd allows any password

long_desc.thetext: Hello, I checked with ldapwhoami and it appears, that when using pwcheck_method: auxprop-hashed (and auxprop_plugin: slapd), no matter what password is provided, the SASL bind to LDAP is always successful.

Created an attachment (id=1498) Example log from transmisson
I attach example log from "sucessful" SASL bind with wrong password which should normally fail.

Log from the following command:
ldapwhoami -H ldapi:/// -Y PLAIN -U p1@proxy.auth -w wrongpass -X dn:uid=jsmith,ou=people,dc=example,dc=org SASL/PLAIN authentication started SASL username: dn:uid=jsmith,ou=people,dc=example,dc=org SASL SSF: 0 dn:uid=jsmith,ou=people,dc=example,dc=org

(From update of attachment 1502) ldapwhoami -H ldapi:/// -Y PLAIN -U p1@proxy.auth -w wrongpass SASL/PLAIN authentication started SASL username: p1@proxy.auth SASL SSF: 0 dn:cn=p1,ou=proxy,ou=auth,dc=example,dc=org

Created an attachment (id=1503) Helper scripts to easy reproduce the BUG (README INCLUDED)
Hi,
These scripts help to reproduce the bug on clean debian unstable (wheezy/sid). At this time, the packages that get installed on debian unstable are:
slapd 2.4.31-1 amd64 libsasl2-2:amd64 2.1.25.dfsg1-5 amd64 libsasl2-modules-ldap:amd64 2.1.25.dfsg1-5 amd64
This openldap server uses new cn=config configuration. To reproduce the bug unpack tarball and follow instructions from readme. Don't do it on a production machine!
It also seems, that auxprop-hashed (with PLAIN auth), lets any authcid to authenticate (even those, for which authzRegexp yields non-existent entry DN).
